          <avActivityHighlights>Slab avalanches and loose snow avalanches are the main danger.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>Little snow fell yesterday. 2 to 10 cm of snow, but less in some localities, fell yesterday above approximately 900 m. In particular on steep slopes medium-sized and, in isolated cases, large slab avalanches are possible as a consequence of new snow and strong wind. &lt;br/&gt; The fresh and somewhat older wind slabs can be released even by a single winter sport participant at intermediate and high altitudes. &lt;br/&gt; Ski touring and other off-piste activities, including snowshoe hiking, call for careful route selection. &lt;br/&gt;</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>Up to 70 cm of snow, and even more in some localities, has fallen since Saturday. &lt;br/&gt; The easterly wind has transported the fresh and old snow. The various wind slabs have bonded with the old snowpack. &lt;br/&gt; Individual weak layers exist in the old snowpack especially on shady slopes.</snowpackStructureComment>
        </BulletinMeasurements>
